06:47.250 --> 06:54.939
How about after World War II, the main 
agricultural business was still counting in the

06:47.250 --> 06:54.939
area? You mean World War I? World War I, I beg your 
pardon. It continued to be that. only cash crop

07:02.834 --> 07:25.554
until Roosevelt's administration when he put in 
the farm program and paid people not to raise

07:02.834 --> 07:25.554
cotton and corn and encouraged them to get into the 
cattle and grain solvent business. That's when

07:25.574 --> 07:32.841
you had the development of grain solvents and also 
your livestock in this country. Up to that time,

07:33.462 --> 07:40.150
they didn't have any improved pastures.

07:40.631 --> 07:46.378
They just had old common crossbred cattle. Nobody 
had any good cattle. And that, you know, Brazos

07:50.003 --> 07:59.615
County land is probably the poorest in the state, 
the natural land. It's either blow sand or hard

07:59.635 --> 08:02.659
pastures. One of the two. But since that

08:05.903 --> 08:17.920
time, in the early 30s, they have been improving 
the land so much that it's real good for grazing. It

08:19.423 --> 08:24.570
never was intended for cotton. But when I was a boy, 
they planted cotton to

08:24.590 --> 08:31.701
the fence. And they planted just enough corn to 
feed their own cattle.

08:40.703 --> 08:50.337
And, of course, everything was farmed by mules, 
most of the mule feed. Now, of course, they had a few

08:50.357 --> 08:51.839
horses to ride. The more affluent had buckets. 
Some had celery.

09:02.974 --> 09:03.375
We had a horse and buggy when I was a child.

09:11.748 --> 09:17.234
Kept that until about 19.

09:17.254 --> 09:17.935
I guess 15.

