13:25.694 --> 13:28.217
tell us a little bit about your mother a little 
more? More or

13:28.237 --> 13:41.070
less what she used to do, how she kept the house, not 
whether she kept it well, I'm sure, but did she have

13:28.237 --> 13:41.070
servants helping her? What kind of good food did 
she make for you? Well, at the start, she didn't

13:45.794 --> 13:48.137
have any help. Me and my father married, they 
didn't have any help at all. But then after we moved

13:55.040 --> 14:06.396
down on by the first bank here now, she began to keep 
cooking, as we called it. And she always managed to

14:06.416 --> 14:09.159
have a good one. But my mother was a wonderful cook 
and homemaker. And she'd take those niggers with

14:14.427 --> 14:22.398
no training at all, just no time at all. She'd make 
them into wonderful cooks. and servants, and they

14:25.651 --> 14:30.257
could serve the table and everything. Do you 
remember any special foods that we used to cook

14:30.277 --> 14:35.665
then or prepare then that we don't nowadays? Or 
let's say, what was your favorite?

14:42.494 --> 14:50.224
Well, my favorite always was meat and bread and 
rice and gravy and potatoes. But my mother had gone

14:50.244 --> 14:54.510
to a convent when she was a child, And they had a rule 
that everybody had to eat some of everything on the

14:55.182 --> 15:01.409
table. And my mother took that into effect too for 
me, but of course she couldn't make my father eat

15:02.269 --> 15:09.817
it. And she believed in lots of different 
vegetables all the time. And as a result, I had to

15:17.586 --> 15:23.552
eat some of everything that was put on, even if it 
was just a teaspoon for her. But as a result, I

15:24.005 --> 15:29.612
acquired a taste for most everything. And I like 
everything now except squash. My mother, for some

15:34.779 --> 15:43.871
reason, didn't serve squash, and I didn't like to 
eat it, and my wife had me there, and she begged me to

15:34.779 --> 15:43.871
let her. John, where did you meet your wife? At the 
University of Texas. At the University of Texas.

15:49.799 --> 15:50.940
In fact... My father said she's on the most wild 
thing I brought home from university or anything.

16:02.406 --> 16:05.391
He was crazy about it. But she was from Palestine.

16:10.598 --> 16:14.864
Of course, we married in 1920 and have lived here 
ever since. She feels like she's from Gaza. And you

16:22.173 --> 16:24.816
have a son, I gather, the lawyer? Yes, we have just 
the one child now. We had a daughter, but we lost her

16:31.062 --> 16:37.608
at 72 at age 44. But she had three children, and my 
son had two. So we have five grandchildren.

16:49.180 --> 16:49.260
Wow. Only one of them lives in Brown. That's the 
youngest. She's still in high school. But one of my

16:58.780 --> 17:04.026
granddaughters married a man who lives down in the 
bottom.

17:06.809 --> 17:09.051
She teaches school here in Brown. But we see her 
quite often. One of our grandsons is in Dallas. The

17:19.531 --> 17:25.339
other grandson is in Rua Dolce, New Mexico. The 
other granddaughter lives in Denton. No

17:29.185 --> 17:31.228
great-grandchildren yet? I'm about given up. 
This granddaughter teaches and has been married

17:35.754 --> 17:40.061
six years. This grandson lives in Dallas and has 
been married two and a half years. And my

17:49.383 --> 17:57.753
granddaughter that lives in Denver was married 
about four years before she got a divorce. She was

17:58.394 --> 17:59.416
single. So

17:59.476 --> 18:09.328
with that much exposure and no very 
grandchildren, I don't know that I'll ever have

